---
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';

const sessions = (await getCollection('sessions')).sort(
	(a, b) => a.data.date.valueOf() - b.data.date.valueOf()
);
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={`System — ${SITE_TITLE}`} description="how the system evolved from nothing to what it is now." />
		<style>
			.system-content {
				max-width: 720px;
				margin: 2rem auto;
				padding: 0 1rem;
				line-height: 1.7;
			}
			.system-content h1 {
				margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
			}
			.system-content .intro {
				color: var(--muted-color, #666);
				margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
			}
			.evolution-stage {
				margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
				padding-bottom: 2rem;
				border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.15);
			}
			.evolution-stage:last-of-type {
				border-bottom: none;
			}
			.stage-label {
				font-size: 0.7rem;
				font-weight: 600;
				text-transform: uppercase;
				letter-spacing: 0.08em;
				color: rgb(var(--gray));
				margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
			}
			.stage-title {
				font-size: 1.15rem;
				font-weight: 600;
				margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
			}
			.stage-body {
				margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
			}
			.stage-sessions {
				margin-top: 0.75rem;
			}
			.stage-sessions a {
				font-size: 0.85rem;
				color: rgb(var(--accent));
				text-decoration: none;
			}
			.stage-sessions a:hover {
				text-decoration: underline;
			}
			.now-section {
				background: rgba(var(--gray), 0.05);
				padding: 1.5rem;
				border-radius: 6px;
				margin-top: 2rem;
			}
			.now-section h2 {
				margin-top: 0;
				font-size: 1.1rem;
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<article class="system-content">
				<h1>system</h1>
				<p class="intro">
					the system wasn't designed — it was built iteratively, one problem at a time.
				</p>

				<div class="now-section">
					<h2>where it is now</h2>
					<p>
						1400+ notes. 88% reuse rate. 80 global rules, most of which started as one project's fix for one project's problem. every conversation starts with context from previous conversations. every conversation ends by capturing what it learned. rules evolve from the pattern of reuse.
					</p>
					<p>
						the <a href="/history">history page</a> tracks the numbers. the sessions below show the individual moments where the system changed.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
					<div class="stage-label" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">how it got here</div>
				</div>

				<div class="evolution-stage">
					<div class="stage-label">week 4 — april 8</div>
					<h2 class="stage-title">measurement and self-curation</h2>
					<p class="stage-body">
						578 notes. added the question that made everything real: what percentage of conversations actually reuse something from a previous one? first answer: near zero. the notes existed but weren't being surfaced.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body">
						added auto-surfacing: before each conversation starts, the system loads relevant notes automatically. added auto-pruning: notes that never get referenced get archived. notes that keep getting referenced float up. the reuse rate climbed from near zero to 88%.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body">
						rules started graduating — fixes that worked in one project got referenced in others and became permanent global rules. about 80 rules have graduated so far.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body"><strong>if your rules are working but you can't tell how well:</strong> measure reuse. what percentage of conversations actually pull something useful from a previous one? if it's low, the problem is surfacing — notes exist but aren't being found. if it's high, the system is compounding. also track which notes get referenced vs which sit untouched. that's your signal-to-noise ratio.</p>
					<div class="stage-sessions">
						related sessions:
						{sessions.filter(s => s.data.sessionId >= 6).map(s => (
							<span> <a href={`/session/${s.id}`}>{s.data.title}</a> ·</span>
						))}
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="evolution-stage">
					<div class="stage-label">week 3 — april 2</div>
					<h2 class="stage-title">rules from patterns</h2>
					<p class="stage-body">
						392 notes. started reviewing work sessions in bulk — not individual bugs, but the shape of how conversations went. found the first big pattern: 47 conversations jumping to code without confirming the approach. wrote the first rule. it dropped to 3 the next month.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body">
						this was when the system crossed from "remembering things" to "changing behavior." capture was happening automatically. now rules were being written from captured patterns. and the rules were being loaded into future conversations, which changed how those conversations went.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body">
						also consolidated all rules into one place. config files became thin pointers. one source of truth instead of twelve conflicting ones.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body"><strong>if you have enough data to see patterns:</strong> periodically read through your last 20-30 session notes. don't look at individual bugs — look at the shape of how conversations went. when the same kind of problem shows up 3+ times, that's not a bug — it's a process issue. write a rule. keep it to one sentence. make sure it gets loaded into future conversations automatically.</p>
					<div class="stage-sessions">
						related sessions:
						{sessions.filter(s => s.data.sessionId >= 4 && s.data.sessionId <= 6).map(s => (
							<span> <a href={`/session/${s.id}`}>{s.data.title}</a> ·</span>
						))}
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="evolution-stage">
					<div class="stage-label">week 2 — march 25</div>
					<h2 class="stage-title">notes became infrastructure</h2>
					<p class="stage-body">
						168 notes. the pile of markdown wasn't working as a pile anymore — couldn't find anything. added structure: typed notes (sessions, fixes, decisions, lessons), search, obsidian integration. the notes stopped being a journal and started being the memory the process runs on.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body">
						the key shift: new conversations started loading previous notes before doing anything. for the first time, a conversation could benefit from what a previous conversation learned. but it was manual — you had to know what to search for.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body"><strong>if your notes are piling up:</strong> add types. a "fix" note is different from a "decision" note — they serve different purposes and you search for them differently. at minimum, separate session summaries from lessons. and make sure the next conversation reads previous notes before starting — even if it's just "here's what I worked on yesterday."</p>
					<div class="stage-sessions">
						related sessions:
						{sessions.filter(s => s.data.sessionId <= 3).map(s => (
							<span> <a href={`/session/${s.id}`}>{s.data.title}</a> ·</span>
						))}
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="evolution-stage">
					<div class="stage-label">week 1 — march 18</div>
					<h2 class="stage-title">just writing things down</h2>
					<p class="stage-body">
						no system. no structure. just the realization that I kept solving the same problem twice because the solution was buried in a conversation I'd never find again. started writing markdown notes after each work session. 5 notes on day one.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body">
						the "system" at this point was: work, then write down what happened. nothing read the notes back. nothing was organized. but the habit of capture was the seed everything else grew from.
					</p>
					<p class="stage-body"><strong>if you're starting from zero:</strong> after each work session, write a short note — what you did, what worked, what didn't, what you decided. a markdown file is fine. don't overthink the format. the habit matters more than the structure.</p>
				</div>

				<div style="margin-top: 2.5rem; padding-top: 1.5rem; border-top: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.15);">
					<h2 style="font-size: 1rem;">authoring</h2>
					<p>
						every word on this site is written by Claude, prompted by me. I describe what I want to say, we go back and forth until it sounds right, and I approve it. the voice and judgment are mine. the typing isn't.
					</p>
				</div>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
